<head>REALITY</head>
    <list type="altnames">
<item>CONCRETE</item>
<item>THE REAL WORLD</item>
<item>REAL LIFE</item>
<item>ACTUALITY</item>
<item>TRUTH</item>
<item>PHYSICAL EXISTENCE</item>
    </list>
    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">真實</item>
        <item xml:lang="och">實</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">
<p>EXIST and NOT ONLY BE IMAGINED.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The current word referring to reality is shí 實 (ant. xū 虛 "pretended reality"), but the word acquired this meaning rather late (meaning "object" in earlier texts).</p>
<p>2. Qíng 情 (ant. wěi 偽 "fake") and chéng 誠 (ant. zhà 詐 "fraudulent") are often used interchangeably to refer to the real facts versus what is pretended or what is merely superficial.</p>
<p>3. Zhēn 真 (ant. jiǎ 假 "faked") refers to the genuine inner state of something, the ultimate truth about it.</p>
        </div>
